<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="seo-techniques">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>marketing</group>
    <domain>seo-manager</domain>
    <summary>Advanced SEO tactics covering schema markup, AI search optimization, social meta tags, pillar-cluster internal linking, and entity optimization for knowledge graph inclusion.</summary>
    <category>seo</category>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
    <tags>
      <tag>seo</tag>
      <tag>schema-markup</tag>
      <tag>json-ld</tag>
      <tag>social-meta</tag>
      <tag>internal-linking</tag>
    </tags>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>SEO Techniques</title>

    <summary>Advanced SEO tactics covering schema markup (JSON-LD), AI search optimization (llms.txt, AEO-ready content structure), social meta tags (Open Graph, Twitter Cards), pillar-cluster internal linking, and entity optimization for knowledge graph inclusion. The core rule: validate all JSON-LD with Google Rich Results Test before deployment — agents produce syntactically plausible but semantically incorrect schema.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Technical SEO signals (structured data, social meta, internal link equity) determine whether content earns rich snippets, AI citations, and proper social previews. Schema markup mistakes are silent — invalid JSON-LD passes the linter but produces no rich results. A pillar-cluster internal link structure distributes authority from high-value pages to long-tail clusters, improving ranking across the topic.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Implementing or auditing schema markup on content-heavy pages (articles, FAQs, products)</item>
        <item>Publishing content that should be cited by AI engines (llms.txt + AEO structure)</item>
        <item>Adding social sharing meta tags (Open Graph, Twitter Cards) to a site</item>
        <item>Building or auditing a pillar-cluster internal link structure</item>
        <item>Optimizing for Google AI Overviews, featured snippets, or voice search</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Site has no indexed content yet — schema on empty pages provides no benefit</item>
        <item>Technical SEO issues (crawl errors, indexing blocks, Core Web Vitals failures) are unresolved — fix fundamentals before adding schema</item>
        <item>Single-page apps without server-side rendering — schema injected client-side is not reliably parsed by crawlers; requires SSR</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="schema-markup-implementation">
      <p>JSON-LD schema patterns for Article, FAQ, Organization, and Breadcrumb types with validation workflow.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Validate all JSON-LD schema with Google Rich Results Test before deployment. Never deploy agent-generated schema without validation.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents produce syntactically valid but semantically incorrect schema: wrong @type values, missing required fields, incorrect nesting. Invalid schema produces no rich results and may generate Search Console errors with no visible symptom.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <section name="validation-workflow">
        <p>Steps to validate schema markup:</p>
        <list>
          <item>1. Generate schema from template or agent</item>
          <item>2. Validate JSON syntax (jsonlint.com or IDE linter)</item>
          <item>3. Test with Google Rich Results Test</item>
          <item>4. Verify no conflicting schema definitions on the same page</item>
          <item>5. Deploy and monitor Search Console for schema errors</item>
        </list>
      </section>

      <section name="schema-type-selection">
        <rule testable="true">
          <statement>Add schema markup in order of impact: Organization (global), Article (all blog posts), FAQPage (any Q&amp;A content), BreadcrumbList (all pages with navigation hierarchy).</statement>
          <rationale>Organization schema establishes brand entity globally. Article schema is required for Google Discover inclusion. FAQPage generates rich result expansion in SERPs. BreadcrumbList appears in search results and improves topic hierarchy signals.</rationale>
        </rule>

        <p>Schema types and their purposes:</p>
        <list>
          <item>Organization + Person: brand and author entity (global, add to header/footer)</item>
          <item>Article/BlogPosting: all editorial content with author and datePublished</item>
          <item>FAQPage: Q&amp;A sections, "People Also Ask" style content</item>
          <item>HowTo: step-by-step tutorials</item>
          <item>BreadcrumbList: all pages with 2+ level hierarchy</item>
          <item>Product + Offer: e-commerce product pages</item>
        </list>
      </section>

      <section name="required-fields-by-type">
        <p>Mandatory fields for each schema type:</p>
        <list>
          <item>Article: headline, author (@type Person, name), publisher, datePublished, image</item>
          <item>FAQPage: mainEntity array of Question + acceptedAnswer pairs</item>
          <item>Organization: name, url, logo (ImageObject), sameAs array</item>
          <item>BreadcrumbList: itemListElement array with ListItem, position, name, item (URL)</item>
        </list>

        <note>The last BreadcrumbList item (current page) should have a name but no item URL. Including a URL for the current page is technically valid but not required.</note>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-search-optimization">
      <p>AI search optimization includes llms.txt standard for AI crawler guidance, entity optimization, and content structure for AI citation.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Create a /llms.txt file at the domain root that provides AI crawlers with a curated, structured overview of the site — similar to how robots.txt guides traditional crawlers.</statement>
        <rationale>AI crawlers lack the context of traditional search crawlers. The llms.txt file provides the canonical summary of what the site is, what content it contains, and what should be excluded — reducing hallucination risk and improving citation accuracy.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>llms.txt implementation:</p>
      <list>
        <item>File location: https://yourdomain.com/llms.txt</item>
        <item>Content: site description, core pages, product pages, contact, exclusions</item>
        <item>Format: Markdown, starting with # sitename and a brief description line</item>
        <item>Update: when site structure changes significantly</item>
      </list>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use the exact same brand name, product names, and key personnel names across all pages, social profiles, and external mentions. Entity name inconsistency fragments knowledge graph representation.</statement>
        <rationale>AI engines and Google's Knowledge Graph build entity representations from consistent co-occurrence patterns. Inconsistent naming ("Faion Network" vs "Faion" vs "faion.net") creates separate, weaker entity nodes instead of one authoritative entity.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>Entity optimization practices:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Brand entity: Organization schema on every page, sameAs links to social profiles</item>
        <item>Author entity: Person schema with sameAs links to LinkedIn, Twitter, GitHub</item>
        <item>Product entities: consistent naming in all descriptions, meta, and schema</item>
        <item>Relationship entities: explicitly link "Author X works at Organization Y" in schema</item>
      </list>

      <section name="ai-friendly-content-structure">
        <p>Content structure requirements for AI citations:</p>
        <list>
          <item>Clear entity definitions in the first paragraph of each page</item>
          <item>Consistent entity naming throughout (no pronoun substitution for first mention)</item>
          <item>Statistics attributed to named sources with publication date</item>
          <item>Dates on all time-sensitive content (datePublished, dateModified in schema)</item>
          <item>Author credentials visible near the article (name, role, expertise signal)</item>
        </list>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section name="social-meta-tags">
      <p>Open Graph and Twitter Card meta tag requirements, plus pillar-cluster internal linking structure and keyword cannibalization fixes.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Open Graph images must be exactly 1200x630px (1.91:1 ratio) and under 8MB. Images outside these dimensions are cropped or rejected by social platforms.</statement>
        <rationale>Facebook, LinkedIn, and most social platforms use 1200x630 as the standard preview image size. Non-conforming images display incorrectly, reducing click-through rates on shared links.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>Open Graph meta tag requirements:</p>
      <list>
        <item>og:title: page title (max 60 chars for optimal display)</item>
        <item>og:description: 155-160 chars, compelling summary</item>
        <item>og:image: absolute URL, 1200x630px, under 8MB</item>
        <item>og:image:alt: image description for accessibility</item>
        <item>og:url: canonical URL (must match rel=canonical)</item>
        <item>og:type: website (default) or article (for blog posts)</item>
        <item>og:locale: en_US (or appropriate locale)</item>
      </list>

      <section name="twitter-card-rules">
        <p>Twitter Card requirements:</p>
        <list>
          <item>twitter:card: summary_large_image for articles and content</item>
          <item>twitter:title: max 70 chars</item>
          <item>twitter:description: max 200 chars</item>
          <item>twitter:image: minimum 506x506px (use the 1200x630 OG image)</item>
          <item>twitter:creator: author Twitter handle</item>
          <item>twitter:site: brand Twitter handle</item>
        </list>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section name="internal-linking">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Every cluster page must link back to its pillar page using anchor text containing the pillar's primary keyword. Pillar pages must link to all cluster pages.</statement>
        <rationale>The pillar-cluster model distributes link equity from high-authority pillar pages to long-tail cluster pages, improving the ranking probability of both. Bidirectional links signal topical relationship to Google.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>Pillar-cluster implementation steps:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Identify 5-10 pillar topics (comprehensive guides on broad subjects)</item>
        <item>Create cluster pages (specific subtopics within each pillar)</item>
        <item>Pillar links to all cluster pages with keyword-rich anchor text</item>
        <item>Cluster pages link back to pillar with target keyword anchor</item>
        <item>No orphan pages — every page has at least one internal link pointing to it</item>
        <item>Maximum 3 clicks from homepage to any page</item>
      </list>

      <section name="cannibalization-fixes">
        <antipattern>
          <description>Multiple pages targeting the same primary keyword (e.g., three different pages about "SDD methodology").</description>
          <reason>Cannibalization splits link equity and authority across multiple pages, weakening all of them. Google chooses which page to rank and often picks the wrong one.</reason>
        </antipattern>

        <p>Fixes for keyword cannibalization:</p>
        <list>
          <item>Fix: 301 redirect weaker pages to the canonical page</item>
          <item>Fix: merge similar content into one comprehensive guide</item>
          <item>Fix: increase internal links pointing to the preferred page</item>
          <item>Fix: use unique primary keywords for each page — no two pages share the same target</item>
        </list>
      </section>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/schema-article.json" purpose="Article schema JSON-LD template"/>
      <template path="templates/schema-faq.json" purpose="FAQPage schema JSON-LD template"/>
      <template path="templates/schema-organization.json" purpose="Organization + Person schema JSON-LD template"/>
      <template path="templates/schema-breadcrumb.json" purpose="BreadcrumbList schema JSON-LD template"/>
      <template path="templates/llms-txt.txt" purpose="llms.txt file template for AI crawlers"/>
      <template path="templates/og-meta.html" purpose="Open Graph + Twitter Card meta tag block"/>
    </templates>

